# Fluff Date: 2026-03-08 15:48:35
<overview>
<p>The Hipparch Cavalry Tank was commissioned in 2562 on the direct orders of First Consul Gregory Amaris of the Rim Worlds Republic, conceived as a fast, aggressive platform to project Republican military power. Designed and built by Diplass Technologies on Apollo, the vehicle was intended to provide the Rim Worlds Army with a capable cavalry asset competitive with Inner Sphere and Star League designs of its day.</p><p>Amaris personally championed the program and ordered thousands produced, though critics within the military argued that political considerations rather than battlefield requirements drove the design. The Hipparch's impressive top speed gave Republic cavalry formations genuine offensive potential, but the design's numerous compromises ultimately defined its legacy as much as its battlefield performance.</p>
</overview>

<capabilities>
<p>The Hipparch's defining characteristic is its exceptional speed, reaching 151 kph on the hover skirt using the Mercury 140 power plant. This velocity made the vehicle one of the fastest combat platforms of its era, allowing Republican cavalry to conduct high-speed raids, screening operations, and pursuit missions that most opponents could not match.</p><p>Armament consists of a pair of Diplass Optimax lasers, one medium and one small, paired with a Harvester SRM 2 missile rack carrying a single ton of reloads. The mix offers reasonable versatility for scout and harassment work, though the payload is modest for a vehicle of its size. Mounting energy weapons on an ICE-powered hull required additional power conversion and heat dissipation equipment, consuming mass that critics argued would have been better spent on armor or firepower.</p><p>The resulting protection is thin, only four tons of Forge 9 Flexweave armor distributed with a slight bias toward the front and sides. This proved inadequate against sustained fire from most opponents. Combined with quality control deficiencies from rushed production, the Hipparch's survivability in a stand-up engagement was genuinely poor, requiring crews to rely on speed and maneuver rather than durability.</p>
</capabilities>

<deployment>
<p>The base-model Hipparch served the Rim Worlds Army primarily as a cavalry and scout vehicle during the Reunification War. Its operational profile centered on high-speed reconnaissance, flank screening, and pursuit missions where its velocity offered a decisive advantage. The vehicle's light armament was suited to harassment and anti-infantry duty, though crews frequently improvised field modifications, mounting machine guns for anti-infantry work or trading energy weapons for a larger missile payload.</p><p>The most extreme field modification, nicknamed the "Hellhorse" by troops, replaced the entire weapon payload and turret assembly with explosives, converting the vehicle into a crude kamikaze weapon driven into enemy formations or encampments. No factory-built variants were ever produced. With the production line destroyed in 2599, surviving Hipparchs soldiered on until attrition claimed the last of them.</p>
</deployment>

<history>
<p>The Hipparch entered service in 2562 as part of First Consul Gregory Amaris's broader effort to modernize the Rim Worlds Army ahead of the Republic's involvement in the Reunification War. Diplass Technologies delivered thousands of vehicles in rapid succession, with production timelines prioritized over quality assurance. Manufacturing defects and field breakdowns accumulated before the design ever reached combat, setting the stage for the problems that would follow.</p><p>When Reunification War operations began in 2577, the Hipparch served as the Republic's primary cavalry asset. In reconnaissance and screening roles the vehicle performed reasonably well, using its exceptional speed to cover broad frontages, maintain contact with enemy forces, and conduct slashing attacks through Taurian and Magistracy formations. Star League observers noted the design's effectiveness as a picket and in high-speed offensive operations.</p><p>The vehicle's battlefield reputation was nonetheless tarnished by its reliability failures. SLDF analysts estimated that as many as one in ten deaths among Republican Hipparch crews resulted from mechanical malfunction rather than enemy fire, a damning indictment of the rushed production program. Star League technicians who observed the Hipparch's costly performance reportedly concluded the Republic's cavalry needed a more sound design, an assessment that contributed to the subsequent development of the J. Edgar hover tank.</p><p>The Hipparch also suffered from misapplication. Despite its light armor, Republican commanders increasingly assigned the vehicle as the anvil in heavy tank maneuvers, using the Hipparch's speed to encircle enemy formations while heavier vehicles delivered the killing blow. The tactic occasionally succeeded but inflicted heavy casualties on the cavalry when enemy armor turned to engage.</p><p>Of approximately 7,000 Hipparchs built, fewer than ninety survived the Reunification War. The production line was permanently destroyed in 2599 during the Wbika coup on Apollo, ending replacement production before most surviving vehicles had completed a decade of service.</p>
</history>

